Reconstruct an economy given a new final demand matrix

Source: R/reconstruct.R
new_Y.Rd

When the final demand matrix changes from Y to Y_prime, this function calculates new use (U_prime) and make (V_prime) matrices that would be required to meet the new final demand (Y_prime).

new_Y(
  .sutmats = NULL,
  Y_prime = "Y_prime",
  L_ixp = "L_ixp",
  L_pxp = "L_pxp",
  Z = "Z",
  D = "D",
  U_prime = "U_prime",
  V_prime = "V_prime"
)

Arguments

.sutmats

a data frame of supply-use table matrices with matrices arranged in columns.
Y_prime

a new final demand matrix or name of a column in .sutmats containing same. Default is "Y_prime".
L_ixp

an L_ixp matrix or name of a column in .sutmats containing same. Default is "L_ixp".
L_pxp

an L_pxp matrix or name of a column in .sutmats containing same. Default is "L_pxp".
Z

a Z matrix or name of a column in .sutmats containing same. Default is "Z".
D

a D matrix or name of a column in .sutmats containing same. Default is "D".
U_prime

the name for new U matrices. Default is "U_prime".
V_prime

the name for new V matrices. Default is "V_prime".

Value

a list or data frame with U_prime and V_prime matrices

Details

Note that inputs L_ixp, L_pxp, Z, and D can be conveniently calculated by the function calc_io_mats.

Internally, this function uses matsindf_apply, and documentation assumes that .sutmats is not NULL and is a data frame. If .sutmats is present, output is a data frame with columns named by string values of output arguments, and input arguments should be character strings that name columns in .sutmats. If .sutmats is NULL (the default), output is a list with items named by output strings, and input arguments should be single matrices or vectors.
